<html>

<title>Ed Facts</title>

<body background="/townhall/FRC/images/bckgnd7.jpg" text="#ff0000" 
vlink="#000000">

<center><h1>ED FACTS - JANUARY 31</h1>
<img src="/townhall/FRC/edfacts/pencil.gif">
</center>
<p>

<font size=+1>

<center><h3>SENATE GOP INTRODUCES LEAD EDUCATION BILL</h3></center>

<p>

Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) last week introduced
the Safe and Affordable Schools Act (S. 1) as a first effort of
Senate Republicans in the 105th Congress to take the offensive
on education.  The bill would provide for low-income voucher demonstration
projects in 20-30 school districts across the nation, and would
make allowances for victims of violence on school grounds to choose
another school -- whether public, private or religious.  S. 1
would allow states to use block grant money under the Elementary
and Secondary Education Act on additional activities, including
parental choice programs, teacher incentive packages and same-sex
schools.

<p>

Title III of the bill is called &quot;The Affordable
College Act.&quot;  It includes several provisions that would
give tax benefits to parents who save for their children's college
education.  For example, parents could place up to $1000 a year
per child into a &quot;Bob Dole Educational Investment Account&quot;
at a 7 percent interest rate.  Disbursements of funds would not
be taxed if used at an accredited college, university or post-secondary
education institution.

<p>

The bill also deals with literacy issues (Title
V), calling for incentive grants for demonstration projects that
would overcome illiteracy with programs of &quot;demonstrated
effectiveness such as systematic phonics.&quot;  Title V would
also establish a 15-member commission to investigate the failure
of the educational system which has resulted in 64 percent of
12th-grade students not reading proficiently.

<p>

S. 1 was introduced on January 21, 1997.  No
legislative action has yet been scheduled.

<p>

<center><h3>EDUCATION SUBCOMMITTEE GOES WEST</h3></center>

<p>

As part of a series called &quot;Education
at a Crossroads,&quot; the House Education and the Workforce Committee
held field hearings in California and Arizona this week.  These
were the first of fifteen hearings Oversight Subcommittee Chairman
Rep. Pete Hoekstra (R-Mich.) plans to hold at sites across the
country this year in an effort to show &quot;what works&quot;
and &quot;what's wasted&quot; in education.  According to Rep.
Hoekstra, the hearings are intended to focus on local successes
while investigating the burden of federal regulation.

<p>

But reports from the first hearing, held in
Napa Valley on Wednesday, indicate that the majority of witnesses
favored government programs.  Representatives Frank Riggs (R-Calif.),
Buck McKeon (R-Calif.) and Hoekstra heard testimony
from 11 witnesses.  Only two of them -- both parents -- pointed
to the failure of spending and federal programs to improve students'
academic performance and the problems with whole language and
Outcome-Based Education.

<p>

Though in the minority, their comments resonated
with the audience of about 200 who had gathered at the New Technology
High School in Napa.  Witness Dorothy Erickson, parent and president
of a National Right to Read Foundation chapter, said her testimony
was interrupted three times by applause, while other witnesses'
praise for California's School-to-Careers program left the audience
cold.

<p>

<i>Ed Facts</i> awaits feedback from the second hearing in Los Angeles, 
on phonics v. whole language, and this morning's hearing in Phoenix, on 
charter schools.  Future hearings in the &quot;Education at a 
Crossroads&quot; series will be announced as information becomes available.

<p>

Members of the Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations:

<p><pre><ul>
Pete Hoekstra (R-Mich.)   Patsy Mink (D-Hawaii)
Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.)   Ron Kind (D-Wisc.)
Van Hilleary (R-Tenn.)    Loretta Sanchez (D-Calif.)
Joe Scarborough (R-Fla.)  Harold E. Ford, Jr. (D-Tenn.)
Buck McKeon (R-Calif.)
Harris Fawell (R-Ill.)
</ul></pre>

<p><hr width=50%><p>

<font size=-1>
<i><b>Ed Facts</b> is a weekly facsimile publication of Family
Research Council, 801 G St., N.W., Washington, D.C.
20001. Phone:  202-393-2100; FAX:  202-393-2134; Legislative
Hotline: 202-783-HOME; Order line:  800-225-4008; Internet Site:
http://www.frc.org.  Suggested annual donation for <b>Ed
Facts</b>: $25.</i>
</font><p>
