<title>February 5, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
February 5, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.<br>
FOR AUDIO SOUNDBITES: Call the FRC Direct NewsLine (202)-393-NEWS x6397
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>TO IMPROVE THE STATE OF THE UNION:<br>
EMPOWER PARENTS, RENEW THE CULTURE,<br>
BAUER SAYS</h2></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> In response to the State of the Union
address by President Clinton and remarks by Oklahoma Rep. J.C.
Watts (R), Family Research Council President Gary L. Bauer called
on Congress today to draw on the strengths of both presentations
to produce an agenda that will serve the cause of family and cultural
renewal. &quot;What we heard last night,&quot; Bauer said, &quot;were
two appeals  that undoubtedly resonated with the majority of Americans,
whose deepest concerns have less to do with technology and trade
than with the temper of our times and the character of our nation.&quot;

<p>

&quot;President Clinton's speech was a deliberate and often successful
reach for the mainstream. <B>About the cultural issues of right
and wrong, the President was almost totally silent</B>,&quot;
Bauer said, &quot;but his remarks on issues from drugs and crime
to safe schools and community empowerment represent the ideals
of most men and women in our nation.  On issues from the nation's
overall economic output, to education, to welfare reform, the
President's praise for American ingenuity and 'call to Action'
in the coming century represent an appropriate summons to this
nation's hopeful spirit.&quot;

<p>

&quot;In the days to come,&quot; Bauer said, &quot;the Family
Research Council will examine the President's detailed proposals
as they emerge. For now, we welcome the fact that the President
has identified numerous needs and taken modest steps in the direction
of meeting them.  He is right to recognize that American families
are profoundly concerned about their ability to educate their
children. To meet this need, he has proposed targeted tax relief
and public school choice. FRC favors tax relief with a much bigger
target, and choice with a much wider array of options. <B>Any
summit designed to increase parental involvement in education
is doomed to fail if it does not maximize the financial resources
of parents</B> so that they can choose better schools for their
children -- of all ages.

<p>

&quot;If we cannot trust parents to choose their child's schools,
how can we ever trust them to be involved in that school in a
constructive way? The family home is our nation's real 'empowerment
zone,' and real tax relief that recognizes the value of human
capital must begin there.

<p>

&quot;We completely agree that politics should stop at the schoolhouse
door. But that cannot happen when we pull all education decision-making
into Washington. After all, every Member of  Congress and the
administration is a partisan politician. The president's proposals
to expand the National Board for Professional Teaching Standards
will only strengthen the stranglehold liberal elites already have
over teacher certification. They will spend our money to threaten
the independence and integrity of private schools, religious schools
and home schools. These schools have been meeting the highest
education goals without federal interference.

<p>

&quot;<B>American kids should be reading by the end of <I>first</I>
grade</B>, not wait until the end of third grade, as the President
proposes. This used to happen all over America. The state of California
is showing real leadership in requiring systematic phonics instruction.
A million volunteers cannot teach a single child to read if they
themselves cannot read.&quot;

<p>

On other issues raised on State of the Union night, Bauer commented:

<p>

<li>&quot;The President's pledge to halve the number of children
who go without <B>health insurance</B> coverage is laudable. Again,
however, we must empower parents to purchase and provide this
coverage.&quot;

<p>

<li>&quot;If we truly want to 'challenge' the nation's artists,
we must ask them to create their works with the same independence
of energy and spirit that animated our nation's writers and painters
for centuries before the advent of the <B>National Endowment for
the Arts</B>. Rescuing this federal handout for a favored few
is morally wrong; moreover, it is thoroughly unnecessary in the
booming economy the President toasted last night.&quot;

<p>

<li>&quot;Perhaps <B>the biggest disappointment of the night</B>
was President Clinton's omission of any mention of the impending
harm that will be done this summer to American values when the
fate of <B>Hong Kong</B> is decided. We cannot celebrate the prospects
for a democratic opening in Cuba and ignore the jaws of tyranny
closing in China.  The President's failure to speak the plain
truth about the <B>deterioration of human rights</B> in the vast
nation of China, truth underscored in his own State Department's
new report, made his strong words about emerging democracies in
Central America and Eastern Europe ring hollow. In those laudable
cases, American Presidents -- particularly Ronald Reagan -- stood
firmly for personal freedom, religious liberty and democratic
self-governance.

<p>

&quot;Who can forget President Reagan's bold challenge: 'Tear
down that wall, Mr. Gorbachev!' The Berlin Wall didn't come down
because of some amorphous sense of 'inevitability.' It came down
because leaders like Ronald Reagan, Pope John Paul II, and Aleksander
Solzhenitsyn had  the moral courage to stand up to oppressive
tyrants.  That kind of moral leadership is needed today on behalf
of more than one billion men, women and children who are systematically
and cruelly abused by a despotic regime in Communist China. Their
six million brothers and sisters in Hong Kong, who were promised
that they would maintain their basic freedoms after July 1, 1997,
likewise need and deserve America's moral leadership to make their
fundamental human rights a reality.&quot;

<p>

<li>&quot;Access to the <B>Internet</B> for every American 12-year-old
from a computer in every home is not merely an issue of fiber
optics, but of the fiber of our people. The President's goal simply
cannot and will not be reached if the problem of pervasive pornography
on the Internet is not resolved. In this regard, what the President's
appointees on the Supreme Court do with the <B>Communications
Decency Act</B> will make all the difference. The same can be
said for most of the family values agenda: neither strong rhetoric
nor wide laws will matter much if our courts continue to erase
what our elected leaders have enacted and signed.&quot;

<p>

<center><h4>FOR MORE INFORMATION ON THE FAMILY RESEARCH COUNCIL
REACTION TO PRESIDENT CLINTON'S STATE OF THE UNION ADDRESS, CALL
THE FRC MEDIA OFFICE AT (202) 393-2100.</h4></center>

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/press/press.html">Other Press Releases</a>]
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/subscribe/subscribe.html.cgi">Subscribe to 
our Press Release E-Mail List</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

<HR SIZE = 3>

