<HTML><HEAD>  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">  <TITLE>Revisioning Defense Speech</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><B><I>From Discovery Institute's Toward the year 2000 Conference, January10, 1997</I></B></P><H2><CENTER>&nbsp;</CENTER></H2><H2><CENTER>&nbsp;</CENTER></H2><H2><CENTER>&nbsp;</CENTER></H2><H1><CENTER>Revisioning Defense: The next four years</CENTER></H1><H4><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1>a speech by<BR>Senior Fellow<BR>Philip Gold<BR></FONT><I>Director of Defense &amp; Aerospace Studies</I></CENTER></H4><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="starbar.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="25" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>G</FONT>ood morning</B>. Thank you for coming. My name  is Philip Gold. I do Discovery's defense and national security work. In  fact, I'm the only person at Discovery who does defense work, so it's always  a treat when I get a chance to talk to somebody besides myself.</P>  <P>As you know, one of the special things about Discovery is that nearly  all of us have multidisciplinary backgrounds and many of us work in more  than one field. Mark Plummer, whom you just heard, does our environmental  work, but he's also an economist. Roberta Katz, who will do the next presentation,  is a high-tech lawyer with a doctorate in anthropology. I also have two  fields: national security and American culture, specifically, life after  the Culture Wars. So when I'm not worrying defense, I'm the resident feminist,  deep ecologist, psychobabble expert, and general purpose postmodernism  guru. I used to think it was kind of a schizophrenic way to make a living,  but now I realize it's more manic-depressive . . . manic referring to the  Pentagon, depressive describing the state of our culture. Or perhaps depressive  describes the Pentagon, and manic refers to the culture.</P>  <P>In any event, I've been asked to predict the next four years in defense  and national security. In one sense, that's impossible. Four years is an  eternity in this Age of Instant Everything, of policies too often based  on CNN inputs and MTV outputs. And, of course, nothing ever gets done unless  it's a crisis or a scandal, preferably both, and nowadays the American  people have hundreds to choose from. In fact, if you believe the surveys,  more Americans are worried about space aliens than national defense.</P>  <P>But in another sense, predicting the future of defense is the easiest  thing in the world. Just think of it as a Seattle weather forecast &shy;  more of the same unless it changes, rain turning to showers, and if you  don't like what you see, just wait fifteen minutes. Something else will  come along. For those preferring a less rosy scenario, I refer you to Mr.  Murphy, and to the First Codicil of Murphy's Law:</P>  <P>Murphy was an optimist.</P>  <P>But at a more serious level &shy; and defense is a serious, a deadly  serious business &shy; I would suggest that, absent a war or a major catastrophe,  these are the years the locust are going to eat. We will waste them arguing  secondary to non-issues, on infighting and turf battles at home, and abroad  on that peculiarly American version of the Politics of Feeling Good about  Yourself, Global Style . . . that odd array of activities, from military  social work to shooting cruise missiles, by which we periodically demonstrate  our resolve to demonstrate our resolve. And I don't think the situation  would be much different, were Bob Dole getting ready to move into the White  House.</P>  <P>We need to get beyond this. So I'd like to take the Discovery approach  &shy; looking farther into the future and farther into the past, in order  to get a better sense of what's happening and what needs to be done. Such  a look, farther into the future and farther into the past, yields the central  proposition of this talk:</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1>The Age of the Wars of Ideology is over. The Age  of the Wars of Terror and Identity has begun. What are we going to do about  it, and how do we prepare for it?</FONT></I></B></P>  <P>To get at this, I would like to look generally at three sets of propositions  and recognitions:</P>  <P>1) American national security policy is decadent. And again, this is  not a partisan issue. It wouldn't be that different under a Dole administration.</P>  <P>2) There is now a conceptual basis for a nondecadent security policy,  and sufficient coherence to turn that policy into strategy.</P>  <P>3) That nondecadent strategy can be supported militarily, provided certain  long-term trends and opportunities are recognized.</P>  <P>After that, I should like to make ten recommendations for the funding  and structuring of the 21st century military.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1>American National Security Policy Is Decadent.</FONT></I></B></P>  <P>I use the word here in two ways. First, in the literal Latin meaning,  <I>decadere</I>, a falling-away, with the implication of a falling-away  from some previous standard. I also use the word in the way Robert Adams,  a literary critic, used it in a few years ago in a book entitled, <I>Decadent  Societies</I>. He defined lowest-common-denominator decadence as &quot;the  deliberate neglect of the essentials of self-preservation.&quot; In both  senses, the word describes the state of American security policy.</P>  <P>The falling-away here is from a previous standard of coherence and purpose.  Through most of the 20th century, American security policy has been both  coherent and purposeful. Sometimes it was not especially realistic &shy;  making the world safe for democracy didn't quite come up to code &shy;  but as for the unconditional surrender of the Axis and the containment  of Soviet communism: Missions Accomplished.</P>  <P>But today, we are told, incessantly told, no such coherence is possible.  This is the New World Disorder, everything is crazy, we have to wait until  it sorts itself out. But it already has sorted itself out. It is very coherent.  To repeat:</P>  <P>The Age of the Wars of Ideology is over. The Age of the Wars of Terror  and Identity has <I>begun.</I></P>  <P>Of course, parts of this new era may not affect or concern us. And American  foreign policy should not be militarized. Our overall policy should be  based upon that supplication in the 1928 Episcopal <I>Book of Common Prayer</I>  where we ask to stand ready &quot;to do good to all men, according to our  abilities and opportunities.&quot; Promoting democracy and human rights,  women's rights and responsible environmentalism, advancing American trade  and strengthening the community of nations, these should be our goals.  Nonetheless, two clear and present dangers have emerged. And if they have  not taken traditional nation-state forms, they are still far from incoherent.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><UL>  <UL>    <LI><I>Weapons of Mass Destruction</I> (WMD) nuclear, biological, chemical,    and high-power conventional, in the hands of those who wish us ill, whether    nation-states, subnational groups, supranational movements, criminals,    terrorist organizations, even individuals. The people I talk to who work    in this field, at both the policy and operational levels, tell me it's    no longer a matter of if WMD will be used against the American homeland.    It's a matter of when. And that use may well occasion the greatest carnage    on this continent since the Civil War.    <LI><I>Violent Expansionist Islamic Fundamentalism</I>. And let's be very    clear here about what we mean. The enemy is not Islam, which is one of    the world's great faiths. Islam has its gracious and humane side, and has    given the world countless cultural treasures. Nor is the enemy the people    of Islam, any more than the Russian people were the enemy during the Cold    War. Nor is the enemy Islamic fundamentalism <I>per se</I>, even though    many of its practices, especially regarding women, may strike us as ludicrous    to abhorrent. Islamic fundamentalism only becomes the enemy when it turns    expansionist and violent, when it spreads its violence across the globe,    alone and in concert with other nations, groups, movements, and criminal    elements. And we must understand that the enmity of Islamic fundamentalism    is now based upon more than American support of Israel, or our historic    (and not always comfortable) relations with &quot;moderate&quot; or &quot;modernizing&quot;    Islamic regimes. It is also based upon a profound detestation of much of    American culture. Some weeks ago, the Iranian government announced the    development of an &quot;Islamic Barbie Doll,&quot; wearing Islamic clothing    and accompanied by a &quot;Ken&quot; doll, dressed as a clerical student.    It sounds ridiculous, but I wouldn't want to be debating a devout Muslim    and have to defend some of the values associated with old Ken and Barbie.    And we do well to remember that some of the condemnations thundered forth    twenty years ago (Has it been that long?) by the Ayatollah Khomeini were    also being voiced by Alexander Solzhenitsyn.  </UL></UL><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1>A Nondecadent Security Policy Is Now Possible and  Necessary.</FONT></I></B></P>  <P>In his history of the Second World War, Winston Churchill called the  1930s &quot;The Gathering Storm.&quot; A storm is gathering again. In fact,  any nondecadent security policy begins with recognition of two gathering  storms: one related to the global proliferation of WMD, the other to violent  expansionist Islamic fundamentalism. Recall those maps so popular during  the Cold War, showing the spreading of communism &shy; the areas shaded  red, the arrows thrust outwards. Imagine such a map of violent Islamic  fundamentalism. The countries already gone (Iran, Libya, Sudan, Afghanistan),  the violent allies (Iraq, Syria), the countries endangered and pressured:  Algeria, Egypt, Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, Turkey, the Islamic areas of Russia.</P>  <P>This recognition of gathering storms, however, can lead in two directions.  One points, as it did in the 1930s, toward denial of the coherence and  imminence of the threat. It points toward a multiplicity of evasions: endless  studies and commissions, counter-terrorism by press conference, business-as-usual,  and the spurious either/or's &shy; defense versus civil liberties, for  example &shy; by which we too often manage to avoid the obvious. The other  way points toward the making of a decision which Americans have made three  times in the 20th century:</P>  <P>Not to withdraw from the world's violence. Not to try to live, as the  theologian Reinhold <I>Niebuhr once put it, as an &quot;island of relative  security in the middle of a global</I> hell.&quot;</P>  <P>But this time, there is a difference. When America made this decision  in the World Wars, the continental homeland was safe. When Americans made  this decision in the Cold War - certainly in the Cold War's second half  - the threat was so overwhelming that little could be done save to trust  in deterrence and hope for the best. This time, the American homeland is  vulnerable. And if the United States chooses to continue to exercise global  leadership, and especially to act in Islamic areas, <B>we're going to get  hit</B>.</P>  <P>If the American people wish to remain engaged with this planet, the  decision must be made in full knowledge of the terrible vulnerability involved.  Nor can there be doubt that, in the struggle against WMD, pre-emption,  prevention, and reprisal will be necessary and legitimate uses of power.  True, the criterion of military success will be what doesn't happen. But  things can &quot;not happen&quot; in many ways. And reprisal of a quality  to deter future attacks will be horrific.</P>  <P>To turn this purpose into policy, and this policy into strategy, two  other recognitions are necessary.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><UL>  <UL>    <LI>The defense of the homeland must come first. A truly isolationist America    would have scant need for defenses. Many would hate us, but few would have    reason to attack us, so long as we left them alone, bought their oil on    their terms, and ignored their crimes. Only an activist America requires    homeland defense. Further, this defense consists of an aggregate of activities,    from ballistic-missile and air defense against limited strikes to counter-terrorism,    drug interdiction, border security, information warfare, and protection    against violent domestic extremists. Currently, these activities are neither    conceived nor pursued as a coherent whole. They need to be.    <LI>The United States must choose its military commitments very carefully.    This excludes the use of the military for global social work, save in very    special circumstances. This also requires a considerable quantity of often    distasteful <I>ad </I>hoc arrangements, from alliances and technology sharing    to acceptance of the fact that (to borrow an Arab proverb) &quot;My enemy's    enemy is my friend&quot; . . . at least for today.  </UL></UL><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1>Turning Policy into Power.</FONT></I></B></P>  <P>A coherent, nondecadent military component of American security policy  must be based upon four recognitions.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><UL>  <UL>    <LI><I>Today, the United States is involved in a unique, historically unprecedented,    </I>asymmetrical arms race. Historically, arms races involved discrete    political entities, i.e., nation-states, empires, or other political structures,    and were easily quantified. Ten tanks were better than five tanks, walls    could defend against chariots, x number of anti-aircraft guns could be    expect to bring down y number of enemy bombers. Today, however, the United    States concentrates on precision-guided weaponry, while the planetary bad    actors &shy; a category which includes far more than nation-states &shy;    build or acquire WMD along with crude but serviceable delivery systems,    from missiles and aircraft to tug boats and trucks. The problem is to make    American power effective against these threats. American conventional forces,    properly maintained and modernized, can defeat any conventional force on    earth. Everybody knows it. But that's only part of the task, and perhaps    not even the most important part. And a lot of people who wish us ill know    that, too.    <LI>However, modern technology provides an astonishing array of new options.    To understand this, it's necessary to go beyond the buzzwords: &quot;Information    Age Warfare,&quot; &quot;Digitizing the Battlefield,&quot; &quot;Third    Wave,&quot; etc. Go back a century. Things were simple. If it happened    on land, the Army did it. The Navy pursued its role at sea. Then the airplane    began to blur the distinction between land and sea combat. Hundreds of    new weapons and systems entered the forces. And a remarkable mixing and    matching began. You could put airplanes on ships: aircraft carriers. You    could put soldiers on airplanes: paratroops and airmobile operations. You    could put armies on ships and land them on defended beaches: the Marine    Corps and the great Army amphibious operations of World War II. You could    put missiles on submarines. The result of all this invention has been that    systems have proliferated, but effects have converged. The &quot;Microprocessor    Revolution&quot; in targeting and command, control, communications, and    intelligence has increased this convergence by orders of magnitude. For    example, in World War II, the best weapon against a tank was another tank;    there were only a couple other ways, none very effective, to do it. Today,    there are over a dozen different ways to fight tanks. It is now possible    to fight tanks with submarines &shy; submerged craft hundreds of miles    from the battle, firing cruise missiles with precision-guided submunitions.    It is now possible, as a recent Naval War College simulation showed, to    sink entire fleets without ever putting a hull in the water. This means    that systems are vulnerable. But it also means that power can be made relevant    to the tasks at hand in many ways.    <LI><I>Think multi-use</I>. Future weapons and systems procurement must    emphasize versatility. In one sense, this is nothing new. A fighter-bomber,    for example, is a good buy because it can attack ground targets or ships    and also fight other aircraft. But today, multi-use means more than different    roles on the battlefield: It means operating in different environments,    from conventional combat to homeland defense. The systems that protect    troops in the field from enemy missiles should be adaptable to protect    the homeland. Ships and aircraft protecting, say, Saudi Arabia, should    also be able to protect Puget Sound. Multi-use now means environments as    well as tasks.    <LI>Finally, this is an age of blurring boundaries. In security policy,    hitherto tidy distinctions between military and law enforcement functions    may begin to break down. Nobody wants a domestic security state; nobody    wants the military on every street corner. Nobody wants massive violations    of constitutional rights and civil liberties. Still, it may be necessary    to make some new divisions of labor for that twilight zone where terrorists,    guerrillas, and the homegrown demented operate. Fortunately, civil liberties    and homeland defense are not either/or, provided the challenge is met honestly,    openly, and publicly.  </UL></UL><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P>Now to ten specific recommendations The first five pertain to money,  the second five to changes in force structure, roles and missions, and  design philosophy:</P>  <P><B>1)</B> Don't cut the defense budget. Real spending is less than half  what it was ten years ago. Five years ago, two years ago, a case could  be made for further cuts. No more. In fiscal 1997, the Defense Department  appropriation is about $264 billion. $275 billion, in real dollars, should  be an adequate base.</P>  <P><B>2)</B> Stop raiding the accounts. Stop using operating money to pay  for peacekeeping, especially. Keep the procurement and R&amp;D accounts  strong.</P>  <P><B>3)</B> Privatize and outsource whenever possible. As a general rule,  if a function doesn't have to deploy anywhere, it can probably be done  better by civilians. This includes everything from aircraft depot maintenance  to mowing the lawns.</P>  <P><B>4) </B>Another round of base closures and realignments. These may  produce greater &quot;cost avoidance&quot; than real savings, but are necessary  nonetheless.</P>  <P><B>5) </B>Downsize. Cut uniformed end strength from the current 1.5  million to one million. Defense must become capital intensive. The days  of cheap &shy; and unskilled &shy; conscript labor are over. This is a  professional force. It is also older and more married; dependents are becoming  an increasingly expensive burden, expecially in medical care.</P>  <P><B>6) </B>Realign roles and missions. This means revisiting the National  Security Act of 1947 and subsequent legislation and agreements. Everything  should be on the table.</P>  <P><B>7)</B> Aerospace first. Aerospace in all its aspects is the great  American comparative advantage. It must be kept. As a general rule, whatever  can be done from the air, probably should be done from the air. Militarily  as well as economically, what's good for Boeing is good for America. And  it may not be too much of a stretch to suggest that, militarily, what's  good for Boeing is good for the world.</P>  <P><B>8)</B> Maintain a robust fleet of 400-450 ships, a 180,000 strong  Marine Corps, and a smaller but modernized Army and a revitalized National  Guard. Yes, &quot;boots on the ground&quot; &shy; the ability to take and  hold territory &shy; will always be necessary. But this tells us little  about how many boots, or how often they'll be used in the WMD era.</P>  <P><B>9) </B>Think multi-use always. This includes both systems and organizations.  The National Guard, for example, is a classic multi-use organization. Its  possibilities along the entire threat array, from homeland defense and  disaster relief to providing the nation's combat reserve for major war  should be explored and enhanced anew. The Guard, too often and too easily  dismissed as archaic, should be viewed from a &quot;clean slate&quot; perspective.  Only then will its enormous potential begin to become apparent.</P>  <P><B>10)</B> Homeland defense. Begin to consider whether and how, at some  point, it might be necessary to create a unified Home Defense Command with  military and civilian elements, subject to rigid civilian oversight and  protection of civil liberties. This isn't necessary now; hopefully, it  will never be needed. But the current arrangements, in which homeland defense  is parcelled out among literally hundreds of agencies and services, working  groups and task forces, may not be adequate to the threat ten or twenty  years from now.</P>  <P>&nbsp;</P>  <P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1>Conclusion</FONT></I></B></P>  <P>Will any of this come to pass, short of a major catastrophe? Hard to  tell. At the moment, in the think tank world certainly, working in defense  is time in the wilderness. Nobody's interested. Nobody's funding it. Perhaps  it will take a major civilian-military movement, akin to the defense reform  movement of the 1970s and 80s, or the airpower advocacies of the interwar  years, to bring it about. They too had their time in the wilderness.</P>  <P>Still, the wilderness can be a challenging place. You meet interesting  people there. And, sometimes, you get to do some good. If the current time  in the wilderness generates a movement that accomplished what the defense  reform and airpower people did, it will be time well spent.</P>  <P>Thank you.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><CENTER><HR WIDTH="52%" SIZE="4"></CENTER></P><BLOCKQUOTE>  <P><CENTER><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1>Dr. Philip Gold is director of defense and  aerospace studies at the Discovery Institute, a Seattle-based think tank,  and director of &quot;ReVisioning Defense: Protecting the People, Defending  the Defenders,&quot; in co-operation with the Heritage Foundation in Washington,  DC.</FONT></I></B></CENTER></P></BLOCKQUOTE><P><CENTER><A HREF="aboutdis.html"><FONT SIZE=-1><IMG SRC="aboutdis.gif"WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></FONT></A><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="current.html"><IMG SRC="image45.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2"></A><A HREF="front.html"><IMG SRC="image46.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2"></A></FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="ggindex.html"><IMG SRC="image47.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2"></A><A HREF="crsc1.html"><IMG SRC="crscbttn.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><AHREF="whatsnew.html"><IMG SRC="image49.gif" WIDTH="99" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" NATURALSIZEFLAG="2"></A></FONT></CENTER></P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</BODY></HTML>
