<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What You Pay for Gas</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<blockquote>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>43 Taxes on Gas</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>By Peter J. Ferrara<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<hr>
<P>
 When you cruise on over to the gas station to fill
up your car's gas tank, you naturally assume that you are paying
for gas.  What you don't realize is that <a href="/atr/tax-presentation/gas1.html">over half of what you
pay goes to the government in taxes</a> rather than for the gas.</FONT>
<P>
The Federal government adds an excise tax of 18.3
cents on every gallon of gas.  Each state then adds an additional
excise tax now averaging 19.4 cents per gallon.  This adds up
to a total of 37.7 cents per gallon.  Based on recent price data
from the Energy Information Administration of the U.S. Department
of Energy, these taxes account for about 28% of what you pay for
a gallon of gas at the pump.</FONT>
<P>
 For a car with a standard 15 gallon gas tank, a
tax of 37.7 cents per gallon adds up to $5.66 per fill-up.  The
Tax Foundation estimates that the average American household will
spend $422 this year on these taxes alone.</FONT>
<P>
 But that is not all.  Before the gas even gets to
the station, the oil producer must pay considerable taxes on its
production and distribution.  These include Federal income taxes,
state income taxes, Federal payroll taxes, capital gains taxes,
unemployment insurance taxes, workmen's compensation taxes, local
property taxes, corporate franchise taxes, sales and use taxes,
and any local income taxes.  States impose severance taxes or
production taxes on each gallon of oil produced.  The companies
must also pay import duties on foreign oil, customs ad valorem
user fees, airport and airway trust fund taxes, harbor maintenance
trust fund taxes, refinery throughport taxes, and pipeline throughport
taxes.  Additional taxes include the corporate environmental tax,
the Superfund tax, the oil spill liability trust fund tax, the
leaking underground storage tank tax, the aquatic resources trust
fund tax, the inland waterways trust fund tax, and the used oil
disposal tax.</FONT>
<P>
 For delivery trucks, the producers must pay heavy
truck excise taxes, tire excise taxes, Federal gas taxes, state
gas taxes, heavy truck highway use taxes, environmental impact
taxes, public highway user taxes, and personal property taxes
on the vehicles.  Finally, the phones at the refinery or on the
pipeline are subject to 3% Federal tax on general telephone services
and another 3% tax on long distance.  Many states also add additional
taxes on telephones averaging another 2%.</FONT>
<P>
 Altogether, the government imposes 43 taxes on the
production of gas.</FONT>
<P>
 The taxes producers pay amount to about 26% of the
income received from the sale of oil and gas products like gasoline.
 As a result, counting the 28% in Federal and state excise taxes
discussed above, a grand total of 54% of what you pay for gas
at the pump goes to the government in taxes rather than for the
gas.</FONT>
<P>
 Suppose the gas you buy costs $1.33 per gallon,
which was the national average for all grades of gas in May. 
Of that total, 72.3 cents would go to the government in taxes,
and only 60.7 cents would remain with the oil producer.  For a
fill-up of a standard 15 gallon gas tank, $10.77 of what you pay
would go to the government in taxes rather than for the gas. 
And none of this counts the impact of regulation, much of which
maybe unnecessary, in increasing gas prices.</FONT>
<P>
 This incredible tax burden falls most harshly on
the poor.  According to the Joint Economic Committee of Congress,
the lowest 20% of income earners pay 7.1% of their incomes on
gas, while the top 20% only pay 1.6%.  In other words, the lowest
income families in America pay over 4 times as much of their incomes
on gas as the highest income earners.  As a result, the high taxes
embodied in the price of gas are consuming over 4 times as much
of the income of the poor as of the rich.</FONT>
<P>
 The excise taxes on gas used to be justified as
a user fee dedicated to paying for the roads.  But today 4.3 cents
of the 18.3 cent Federal excise tax is openly dedicated to general
government expenses rather than roads.  Another 2 cents is dedicated
to mass transit.</FONT>
<P>
 Much of the remainder has not been spent on roads
in recent years either.  Instead, the Federal government uses
the money for general expenses and puts an IOU in a so-called
Highway Trust Fund.  That IOU would be turned in for cash from
the government to be used for highways, if and when the Federal
government so chooses.</FONT>
<P>
 If you are concerned about the high cost of gasoline,
you should focus on the real problem -- your greedy and overreaching
government.</FONT>
<P>
<hr>
<FONT SIZE=2>Mr. Ferrara is general counsel and chief economist
at Americans for Tax Reform.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>1320 18<SUP>th</SUP> Street N.W., Washington,
DC  20036  (202) 785-0266.</FONT></CENTER>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
</HTML>
